  "doc_id": "51807",
  "text": "Our results demonstrate that Syt IV resides on DCVs and microvesicles in peptidergic nerve terminals of the posterior pituitary. Comparisons between the nerve terminals of wild-type and Syt IV knockout mice showed that this protein can either enhance or inhibit Ca 2+ -triggered exocytosis, depending on the amount of Ca 2+ entry. Syt IValso changes the conductance of DCV fusion pores and modifies the kinetics of endocytosis. Prior studies have suggested diverse locations and functions for Syt IV, which is expressed in various cell types. We focused on Syt IVat biologically relevant levels in its native environment, and many of the disparities in the literature probably stem from technical aspects of the various expression protocols and differences in the targeting of an expressed protein in different experimental systems. The high levels of Syt IV that we observed in the posterior pituitary compared with other brain regions indicate that it has a special role in neuropeptide function. Given the similarities between synaptic vesicles and endocrine microvesicles [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , our finding that Syt IV resides on microvesicles and alters their exocytosis raises the possibility of a direct role for Syt IV in regulating synaptic transmission.",
